{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_myrtle_ver01/data/56022775/00541313400/1949031901/0027.xml":{"full_text":"Official Weekly Publication\nTRAINMANNEWS\nBrotherhood of Railroad Trainmen\nA. F. Whitney, President\nW. P. Kennedy, General Secretary and Treasurer\nPublished weekly at 2457 East Washington Street,\nIndianapolis 7, Indiana\nEditorial Office: 1244 Standard Building, Cleveland 13, Ohio\nPOSTMASTER: Send Forms 3578 or 3579 to Business Office\n1348 Standard Bldg., Cleveland 13, Ohio\nAll communications or news items for publication in TRAINMAN\nNEWS must be in the office of the Editor by 5:00 P. M. of Monday\nof the week for which publication is intended.\nEntered as second-class matter January 30, 1947, at the post office\nat Indianapolis, Indiana, under the Act of August 24, 1912.\nSubscription rate $1.00 per year: Individual copies 10 cents\nNo commercial advertising accepted.\nIrvin S. Lippe, Editor\nAssociates: George H. Hennemuth II, Louis E. Corsi\nVol. 3. No. 12\nMarch 19, 1949\nHeli Not Progress\nThe Brotherhood\u2019s fight against the proposed overland\nconveyor belt scheme in Ohio is of vital importance to the\ninterest of rail workers everywhere and warrants the support\nof all Americans who are concerned with national welfare.\nWidely touted by its promoters as industrial \u201cprogress,\u201d\nthe belt idea is actually a plan to make a few rich men richer.\nIt has nothing whatsoever to do with advancing the interests\nof the entire community.\nThe proposed electrically-operated conveyor would trans\nport coal from the Ohio River port of East Liverpool to Lake\nErie boats and iron ore from Lake Erie to Cleveland, Youngs\ntown and the Ohio River.\nIt would knock many railroaders out of jobs, but even\nworse it would deprive several railroads of their most impor\ntant business and ultimately force them to suspend opera\ntions, with the resulting economic stagnation and chaos to\nhundreds of communities along the way.\nWe can hardly see how it would be useful in wartime for\nexpeditious transportation of troops and materiel, 105 milli\nmeter guns, for example. The huge elevated python would be\nan elegant sitting duck for enemy bombers. What then would\ncarry vital defense materials, with rail service dried up?\nWould the conveyor belt fill the bill to keep our great in\ndustries going and would it be flexible enough to provide all\nthe varied and complex and vital services now offered by the\nrailroads\nNothing in the proponents\u2019 arguments thus far indicate\nthat it would.\nIn fact, President Whitney hit the nail on the head two\nweeks ago when he charged the scheme with being just an\nother plan of the big corporations for more profit. \u201cYou know\nthis won't bring prices of steel down, or coal either. They will\njust make a big cry and keep the profits,\u201d he declared.\nThe long distance conveyor belt does not mean progress.\nIt means unemployment and suffering for many railroaders.\nIt means unemployment and suffering for those communities\nthat would inevitably be deprived of regular rail service. It\nmeans weakened national defenses at a most crucial period in\nour history.\nOhio Brotherhood members should write and wire their\nsenators and representatives in the state capital of their mili\ntant opposition to this monstrous proposition.\nBrotherhood members thruout the U. S. and Canada\nshould be on the watch for such schemes in their sections.\nDon\u2019t be fooled. The overland conveyor belt for long dis\ntance hauling would be a liability to the interests of most\nAmericans. It is not progress.\nGlover Addresses Organizers\nL\nA distinguished labor statesman held meetings the other\nday in St. Louis\u2019 Carpenters\u2019 Hall.\nHe and eight other lesser lights were on the stage, while\neight yard men, principally representatives of the Brother\nhood, composed the audience. And while the distinguished\nMr. Glover rang loud, the acoustics almost deadened the ears\nof the stingers.\nThe SU president went to confession at both meetings\u2014\nat 10 a.m. and 30 p.m.\u2014by stating that no more funds were\navailable for additional organizers and that they could not\ntake a vote due to insufficient membership.\nHow tragic! Poor Glover! Making a confession before\nan audience of trainmen.\nApparently his wet nurse is withholding funds which\nwere poured forth so liberally for about 90 days because Mr.\nGlover and his tiny group have failed to make any progress.\nThe SU has existed on empty promises to the few suckers\nin yard service who have followed its banner, and now that it\nis running out of promises appears to be bankrupt.\nTom Cashen could have done a better job.\u2014AFW.\nWEY,SoMEBOpY\nStop him\nKTeNY\n\u2014Koo!\nA\nKCoNaxsss\nYour Money\u2019s Worth\nBy MARY SHERIDAN\nTrainman News Staff Writer\nHow are we doing? Whenever people get\ntogether, someone in the group is bound to\nsay, \u201cDo you think we\u2019ll have a depres\nsion?\u2019\u2019\nStudying what the experts and business\nmen and the business press say gives me\nthe impression that nobody knows the an\nswer. One of the most common-sense pre\ndictions is the Joint Committee on the\nEconomic Report\u2019s forecast of another\nboom year, labeling as \u201cpremature\u201d the talk\nof recession or depression. This is bolstered\nby the fact that while unemployment has\nincreased and prices have dropped in some\nlines, production has not slowed up.\nThe unpleasant fact of 3,200,000 unem\nployed in February\u2014the highest number of\njobless since 1942\u2014is a disturbing one,\nrelieved only by the reassuring news that\nthe rate of increase has slowed down. The\nspring months just ahead should bring us\nmore decisive information about employ\nment.\nOur grocery bills are down. Meat, fresh\nand canned vegetables, dairy products, and\nfresh fruit have dropped in price all over,\nthe country, with the possible exception of\nnorthern California, where prices haven\u2019t\nchanged much from a year ago.\nFood, according to a recent survey of na\ntional living costs by the New York Times,\nis the one necessity in which \u201csizable price\ncuts\u201d have been passed along to consumers.\nClothing sales offer alert shoppers a chance\nto save on men\u2019s, women\u2019s, and children\u2019s\nclothes, but the sales are most frequent in\nthe large cities where there is more compe\ntition. Price cuts on clothing staples are\nspotty.\nFuel and light costs are up. So is the cost\nof shelter in many parts of the country.\nMilk, most often, has dropped only a penny\na quart. Bread prices have not come down.\nSo, altho food prices are down, altho\nChevrolets are $10 and Cadillacs $40\ncheaper, altho some electric appliances are\ncheaper, the consumer is not yet able to\nsave enough on necessities or luxuries to\nstay solvent or build up savings. Consumer\ncredit is rising, which is a polite way of\nsaying that more of us are going in debt.\nNow that the Federal Reserve Board has\nrelaxed the installment buying terms of\nRegulation W, more people will be tempted\nto go in debt. Buyers can now buy refrigera\ntors and all other goods under Regulation\nW except cars for 15 per cent down, paying\noff the balance in 21 months. Purchase of\ncars still requires (and a good thing too)\na down payment of one-third the retail\nprice.\nThe high cost of bread, despite the drop\nin wheat prices, highlights a consumer di\nlemma. Since bread is a necessary staple in\nmost homes, consumers will pay any asking\nprice to have it. (Today\u2019s high bread prices,\nalas, haven\u2019t pushed us cooks into baking\nour own bread.)\nWho has been getting the profits from\nbread? Wheat prices dropped from $2.81\na bushel in January, 1948, to $1.98 in Oc\ntober. Bread has kept right on averaging\n14 %2 cents a loaf. According to an analysis\nof the Bureau of Agricultural Economics,\nthe miller\u2019s profits have not increased.\nWages in the baking industry during this\nabove period went up only 4.6 per cent. The\ndrop in wheat prices, which should have\ndropped the price of bread for consumers,\nhas increased the profits of the commercial\nbakers.\nPerhaps it is an exaggeration to call it\n\u201calmost a household word,\u201d but the Bureau\nof Labor Statistics\u2019 (BLS) cost-of-living\nindex has become a well-known yardstick of\nour economic condition. The index repre\nsents the market prices of food, other goods,\nand services as bought by moderate income\nfamilies in large cities.\nThe Department of Labor, of which the\nBLS is a part, wants to modernize the index\nso that it will be a more accurate reflection\nof the average consumer's postwar buying\nhabits. Secretary of Labor Tobin has asked\nCongress for funds to start the overhauling\nprocess after July 1.\nLabor officials point out that as computed\nnow the BLS index is old-fashioned; it is\nbased on 1934-36 buying habits and doesn\u2019t\ninclude the prices of frozen foods, the cost\nand operation of mechanical refrigerators,\nand other technological changes in our eat\ning, clothing, and living habits during the\npast 15 years.\nThis request has particular significance,\nsince the BLS index is often used as a\nstandard measuring rod of consumer prices\nby employers and unions in discussing wage\nagreements. Union leaders argue that a\ncost-of-living index computed on standards\nand habits of 15 years ago doesn\u2019t really re\nflect today\u2019s living costs.","height":"20772","width":"14028"}}
